segments.text: First time a student told me that he's going to die.
Let's see, any tragedy, sad, truly sad realities you remember?
I guess everything pales compared to last fall's loss.
Yes.
But I've had students that would be enrolled in the class, commit suicide,
be killed in car wrecks.
And I've had them tell me they had HIV positive.
We've had graduate students.
I don't know the person's name.
But we, through what we've worked with international students,
I don't think the department itself put any money into getting the body back home.
I just, I don't know the particular.
You know, one of the, one of the,
one of the latest things, we had a, we had a student from Mexico lose a 12-year-old daughter here
Christmas a year ago, over the Christmas holidays, she died and it turns out that she'd undergone a lot of tests here.
Apparently, the, the parents didn't know enough to, to check and get, get the results of the test.
Because I remember she had a brain tumor or something.
She, she'd undergone a lot of tests.
But they had results.
Suggesting it was a real problem.
Vacation to Mexico with a girl without getting the test.
Excellent family.
I'm not sure the students made it.
I certainly didn't know.
Some of the, so some of those things happened.
And you, we had a student drown.
That brought a unique knaff.
This guy probably knew more about knaff than anybody in the world.
And brought him in here as a graduate student.
And he, he drowned.
I don't know.
Some of it.
What about some, some of the highlights?
See how successful they've been.
Just the other day, a fellow walked in.
Very funny.
You have, you have those kinds of guys.
It was just a great experience.
If they ever get a chance to come back to the States.
That fellow from Korea had attended meetings in Orlando, Florida.
He had other friends in the community, but.
All right.
Now you thought things were beginning to move forward.
You and your colleagues under Mr.
Rudder and then under Williams.
I just, I mean, knowing Jarvis as I do, I just cannot.
To this day.
That was painful.
Yeah.
Yeah.
Absolutely painful.
Right.
That was just not good.
But he, he was not cut out for being interested.
All right.
Then had an acting president for a year.
Dr. Vandenberg.
Did you and your colleagues.
Those years.
Under his leadership.
I think quite well.
This is about.
He was here 19 years.
He actually was, he had longer than, longer than Dr. Vandenberg.
So he gets here what year?
He got here in 1980.
Started through 1999.
Describe his men.
He was not here in, you know, he was not here in a period of growth.
He was here more in a period of retrenchment for the department.
So that made, I think that made the management much more difficult in a sense.
He never, he never had to quote clout for the upper administration of Marshal Woodward.
On the other hand, he gets lectures and several.
So we, we usually get him in about 30 or 40 different.
So we actually have him in the classroom as many hours as we'd have him if he taught a class.
But we put him in contact with me.
We put him in contact with many, many more students.
Do the students seem to appreciate what, what he is?
I mean, if you've never heard the man speak, it'd be worth hearing.
So they, they are appropriately respectful and impressed.
Oh yeah.
He is, he is an amazing man.
He dedicated the Borlaug Center over here last year.
Were you there under that dedication?
Well, it gives you some indication of the man.
He was, he was limited to 15 minutes.
I wouldn't have thought there'd be any way in the world you could get him up and down in 15 minutes.
Maybe it was 10 and he actually, we got him up and down in 15.
I mean, I believe he was only supposed to take 10 minutes.
Well, he let me, let me critique his remarks.
But two or three officers sitting out there as Dr. Borlaug spoke, and I leaned over to the guy next to him and I said, he's all stripped now.
But, but he was.
But, but he was talking about all of the adverse publicity about the genetically modified organisms.
And how too little had been done to educate the public as to what these were coming on.
And, and sitting behind him on the stage was Dr. Boyne and Dr. Douglas.
There were two members of the Board of Regents.
I don't remember who else was up there.
Maybe it did on the controller.
It did on the...
Anyway, I know, I know Douglas and Boyne and at least two members of the Board.
And Borlaug turned around while he was talking and just shook his finger in the face every one of them about what we needed to be doing.
I mean, the guy's brassy.
He's absolutely, and, and he can do it and get by with it.
You know, he, he can do it because he's a very gracious.
He's just an extremely gracious, unassuming guy.
Who put him down there in a windowless 120-square-foot office.
He never said a word.
Now, he's been a part of the department for about a decade now or longer?
Yeah, longer than that.
How did he come to be?
I don't know.
You'd like to ask somebody else about that?
You don't know who, who linked him up?
Well, I know Perry Atkinson had a big time role in it.
Perry, of course, Perry became a National Academy person.
Yes, yes.
And Norm was National Academy.
Okay, so.
I'm sure that Perry got acquainted with Norm in that setting.
So, I expect it was a Perry Atkinson.
All right.
Now, Dr. Atkinson didn't come out of this department, did he?
No, he's out of entomology.
Entomology.
All right.
And he moved up into the administration.
Yep.
Did you and your colleagues feel positive about that?
Did you feel that it was good to have him?
Generally so.
Nobody ever accused Dr. Atkinson of being a good class teacher.
His standard statement, I've heard, I never heard Dr. Atkinson say that, but I've heard
him say it.
It's all three credit courses.
People like such a big deal about teaching a three-hour course.
Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.
I've got to tell you now, before we forget to do it, I've got to tell you about the low
light in my home.
Oh, good.
Good.
The whole three years.
Okay.
I tilled my garden that year because it was unbelievable.
When we were hiring all these people in the 75, 80 period, we were getting money on
the university side.
We were not getting any money on the experimental side.
So we hired, about the same time, two young faculty members, 100% teaching.
Mm-hmm.
No experimental station partner or author on some of their papers.
He wouldn't have any part of any of that.
He thought, you know what?
I don't know.
He thought, well, here's where the student finished and published at college level.
I measured him by research publication.
Absolute retreat.
In a way, I could see that part of it was his own doings, his own stubbornness and hard-headedness.
At the same time, I felt like if the man had the kind of support that he had within his
department for his contributions, the people who knew his work best.
Who the heck was somebody up there to say this is the weakest person they ever saw?
Now that was, that really, that really got to me.
And I just, man, I worked my old garden.
I never had anything bother me so much in my whole career.
Philosophically, how does a first-rate land-grant school appropriately
deal with that?
Well, it's been a minute.
I have an average of more like one every two years, kind of thing.
But I can't see that that's held me back in any way at any level in the institution.
So, you know, I take a dim view when people say that teaching doesn't get the credit it
deserves or advice doesn't get the credit it deserves.
I think, I think generally it does.
My posture is.
If you take those three areas, there are very, there are comparatively few people that
excel in any one of the three.
